== Records ==
According to the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' (Keikō Tennō, Year 40, Seventh Month, Sixteenth Day entry), Kibi no Takehiko and {{ill|Ōtomo no Takehiko|ja|大伴武日連|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtomo no Takehiko|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} accompanied Yamato Takeru during his eastern expedition. Later that year, Kibi no Takehiko was dispatched to oversee the Echizen region before rejoining Yamato Takeru in Mino. After Yamato Takeru fell ill, Kibi no Takehiko carried his final message to Emperor Keikō{{Sfn|Kibi no Takehiko (Ancient Lineages)|2010}}.

In the ''[[Kojiki]]'' (Keikō Tennō's account), a figure identified as "Misuki Tomomimi Takehiko" (御鉏友耳建日子) was a companion of Yamato Takeru during his eastern expedition. It is unclear whether this refers to Kibi no Takehiko{{Sfn|Kibi no Takehiko (Ancient Lineages)|2010}}.

Additionally, the ''Shinsen Shōjiroku'' (Right Capital, Imperial Line: Luhara clan) records that during Keikō Tennō's reign, a descendant of Wakatakehiko no Mikoto named "Kibi Tatehiko no Mikoto" was sent eastward to subdue the barbarians. After completing his mission in the Abe-Luhara region, he returned victorious and was granted the land.

== Descendants ==
=== Clans ===
The ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|en|Shinsen Shōjiroku|qid=Q1045362|lt=Shinsen Shōjiroku|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku}}'' lists the following clans as descendants of Kibi no Takehiko:
* Left Capital, Imperial Line: {{ill|Shimotsumichi Asomi|ja|下道朝臣|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimotsumichi Asomi|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} - Descended from Wakatakehiko no Mikoto through Kibi no Takehiko.
* Right Capital, Imperial Line: {{ill|Magami-be|ja|真髪部|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Magami-be|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} - Descended from Wakatakehiko no Mikoto through Kibi no Takehiko.

=== Provincial Governors ===
The ''[[:en:Sendai Kuji Hongi|Sendai Kuji Hongi]]'' ("[[:en:Kokuzō Hongi|Kokuzō Hongi]]") lists the following provincial governors (''kokuzō'') as descendants of Kibi no Takehiko:
* {{ill|Luhara Kokuzō|ja|廬原国造|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Luhara Kokuzō|1=Ihohara Kuni no Miyatsuko|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11486465}}
*: Under Emperor Seimu (志賀高穴穂朝), Kibi no Takehiko’s son Okabehiko no Mikoto was appointed governor of Luhara Province. This corresponds to modern-day {{ill|Suruga Province|en|Suruga Province|qid=Q864170|lt=Suruga Province|1=Suruga Province}}'s [[:en:Ihara District|Ihara District]]<ref>''Studies on the Kokuzō System - Source Material and Analysis,'' Yagi Shoten, 2013, p. 176.</ref>.

== Interpretation ==
Based on the ''Nihon Shoki'' (Ōjin Tennō, Year 22) and ''Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku'' (Engi 3), Kibi no Takehiko was positioned as the founder of various clans governing the Kibi region. This includes the Shimotsumichi, Kamitsu, Mino, and Kasa clans, as well as the Enō clan{{Sfn|Kibi no Takehiko (Ancient Lineages)|2010}}. Scholars suggest Kibi no Takehiko is the true ancestor of the Kibi clan and that figures such as {{ill|Kibitsuhiko-no-mikoto|en|Kibitsuhiko-no-mikoto|qid=Q65318|lt=Kibitsuhiko no Mikoto|1=Kibitsuhiko-no-mikoto}} and Wakatakehiko no Mikoto, attributed as his father or grandfather, were later constructs to align the Kibi lineage with the imperial family<ref>Ryoichi Onosato, "Genealogy and Reality of the Kibi Clan," in Kiyoshi Kato (Ed.), ''Japanese Ancient Kingship and the Provinces'' (Yamato Shobo, 2015), ISBN 978-4-479-84081-7.</ref>.

Kibi no Takehiko's participation in Yamato Takeru's legend also suggests the Kibi clan's involvement in shaping this mythology{{Sfn|Kibi no Takehiko (Ancient Lineages)|2010}}.

